Yin and Yang are two opposite categories in ancient Chinese philosophy.
Every thing and phenomenon in nature has two opposite aspects - Yin and Yang, which is manifested mainly in their mutual restraint and struggle.
The discordance between water and fire may bring about a morbid condition named "breakdown of the balance between the heart and the kidneys", marked by insomnia, palpitation, dysphoria, lassitude in the loins and legs, or nocturnal emission in men, coition during dream in women, and so on.
As for respiratory activities, since the lungs govern the exchange of gases and the kidneys the reception of air, sufficiency of the kidney-Qi helps the inhaled air sent down from the lungs to be received in the kidneys, as the saying goes " The lungs are the dominator of Qi and the kidneys its root".
The human body as an integral whole is permeated with relationship of unity of the two opposites.
An excess of Yin or Yang beyond its normal level brings about a pathological change.
An excess of Yin (or Yin pathogen) is a pathological change resulting from Yin's excess beyond normal level.
"An excess of Yin produces cold"means that since Yin is associated with cold, excessive Yin will cause cold syndrome of excess type.
Insufficiency of Yin or Yang is a pathological change in which either Yin or Yang is below normal level.
Deficient Yang is unable to restrain Yin, thus leading to relative hyperactivity of Yin and cold syndrome of insufficiency type.
When Yin is deficient, it is unable to restrain Yang, leading to relative hyperactivity of Yang and asthenic heat-syndrome.
It is a method of treatment for Yang deficiency syndrome.
It's a method for treating Yin deficiency syndrome.
From the above it can be seen that the body fluid derived from food and drink is formed by the preliminarily digestive action of the stomach, that of the small intestine in separating the refined substances from the dross and that of the spleen in transport.
Five elements refer to wood, fire, earth, metal and water.
It implies that one kind of thing can promote, increase or generate another.
It implies that one kind of thing can inhibit or restrict another.
Each of the twelve regular channels as well as the Du and Ren channels possesses a major collateral, plus an extra large splenic collateral.
The Chong channel ascends to the head and descends to the foot, permeating throughout the whole body and serving as the conmunication centre for the circulation of Qi-blood. It can regulate the Qi-blood of the twelve regular channels.
These are the theoretical concepts derived by ancient people from their sinple cognition of the five kinds of matter (namely, wood, fire, earth, metal and water) By abstracting they constituted a basic principle with which to analyse various things and their properties, and to study the inter relation between them.
It is a therapeutic principle for treating deficiency-syndrome, based on the concept of the mother- child relationship of inter-generation of the five elements.
This is a therapeutic principle for treating the excess-syndrome, based on the theory of the mother-child relationship of inter-generation of the five elements.
The fire in the five elements originally represents the heart of the five Zang-organs, but since the doctrine of Mingmen sprang up, the fire from Mingmen has much been said to warm the whole body.
Here earth refers to the spleen and water to the kidneys.
"Zang" refers to internal organs of the body; "Xiang" here refers mainly to the outward physiological and pathological manifestations.
By viscera-phase doctrine is meant a theory that by observations on the physiological and pathological manifestations of the human body, a study can be made of the physiological functions and pathological changes of its various viscera, their interactions and the interrelationship between visceral organs and structures of the body and the external environment.
The gallbladder, stomach, small intestine, large intestine, urinary bladder and tri-Jiao (triple energizer or warmer) are known collectively as the six Fu-organs.
For instance, rheumatic fever is manifested by migratory pain in the joints of limbs, known as "wind arthralgia".
The heart in TCM refers to both its anatomical entity and specific functions.
This function involves two aspects: the maintenance of blood circulation and the control of vessel movement.
This function consists in that the heart houses the mind or the heart governs Shen.
This denotes that the physiological functions of the heart are related to joy, one of man's seven modes of emotion.
The heart-Qi travels upward and reaches the tongue.
The lungs are situated in the thorax one on each side.
This function involves two aspects: the regulation of Qi of the whole body and the control of respiration.
Literally, dispersing, here, means upward diffusion and outward sending of lung-Qi, and descending, lowering of lung-Qi and keeping the respiratory tract clean.
Water nietabolism, here, refers to a physiological process by which body fluids are produced, distributed and discharged.
Melancholy and sorrow as two modes of emotion, though slightly different from each other, exert roughly the same influence on physiological functions of the human body.
Nasal discharge is the mucus secreted from mucous membrane of the nose, which performs the function of moistening nasal meatus.
The nose connects with the larynx and further communicates with the lungs, the nose and larynx are the passageway of respiration, as the old sayings go:"The nose is the external orifice of the lungs"and"The larynx is the gateway of the lungs".
Pathogenic factor, called pathogen for short, refers in a broad sense to all disease-producing factors, such as six climatic conditions in excess, epidemic pathogenic factors, emotional irritation, phlegm retention, blood stasis, etc.
As the spleen and stomach are the source of growth and development of Qi-blood, the muscles in the whole body rely on the supply of nutrients from foodstuffs transported by the spleen and stomach, whereby they are rendered well-developed and strong.
Saliva is a clear watery fluid in the mouth.
For example, the morbid condition marked by accumulation of heat in the intestine and stomach is accompanied by "fecal impaction due to heat with watery discharge.
On the other hand, genuine deficiency with pseudo-excess syndrome or "symptoms of excess in ex treme deficiency", usually results from the dysfunction of the Zang-Fu organs and their failure to transport and transform nutrients.
The tendons, attached to the bones and aggregating around the joints, are a kind of tissue joining muscles to the joints.
The kidneys are situated in the waist, one on either side of the spinal column.
One of the chief physiological functions of the kidney-essence is to promote the growth and development of the body.
The reproductive power of the human body bears a close relation to the state of the kidney-essence.
This important function of the kidneys is concerned with the regulation of conveyance, distribution and discharge of body fluids, and with maintenance of the balance of water metabolism within the body through the functioning of the kidney-Qi.
Spittle is a thicker fluid in the mouth.
Hearing of the ear depends upon whether the kidney-essence is replete or not.
The stomach, located in middle-Jiao, also known as gastric cavity, is divided into three parts: upper middle and lower.
The food mass coming from the mouth through the esophagus enters the stomach via the cardia and is received and contained by the stomach.
Food passes from the mouth through the esophagus into the stomach, i.e., the stomach receives and contains all kinds of foodstuff.
The term"stomach-Qi"usually has two senses: narrow and broad.
The small intestine is a much longer tube-like organ in the abdomen, with its upper outlet connected by the pylorus with the lower outlet of the stomach and its lower outlet communicating with the upper outlet of the large intestine through the ileocecum.
The pathogenesis of this morbid condition lies in that blockage of Qi is caused by impediment of its external flow.
The large intestine is situated in the abdomen, with its upper end connected with the small intestine by the ileocecum and its lowest end being the anus.
Tri-Jiao (SanJiao), or triple energizer (warmer), a general term for the upper, middle and lower Jiao, is regarded as one of the six Fu-organs.
Tri-Jiao, as a passageway for ascending, descending, in-going, and out-going of Qi, is the site of its functional activity within the body, so it has the function of passing various kinds of Qi.
The upper-Jiao refers mainly to the thorax above the diaphragm, including the heart, lungs and head as well.
The lower-Jiao refers generally to the lower portion of the body cavity below the stomach, consisting of the small intestine, large intestine, kidneys, urinary bladder, etc.
The marrow is classified into bone marrow, spinal cord and the brain, all of which are manufactured by the kidney-essence.
The uterus, or womb, situated in the lower abdomen posterior to the urinary bladder in women, is a reversed pear-shaped organ for occurrence of menstruation and breeding of the fetus.
The Tiangui is a kind of refined nutritious substances transformed from the kidney-essence and perfoms the function of promoting and maintaining the growth, development and reproduction of the body.
The channels of the lungs and the large intestine are interrelated to each other.
As the channels of the spleen and the stomach are interrelated to each other, "the spleen and the stomach are said to be interior-exteriorly related".
Owing to the interrelation between the kidneys and the urinary bladder through channels, both are said to be "interior-exteriorly related".
Since the heart governs blood and blood circulation while the lungs dominate Qi and respiration.
The heart governs blood, and the spleen keeps blood flowing within the vessels and provides Qi-blood as the source of growth and development.
The relationship between the lungs and the spleen is chiefly manifested in two aspects(1) formation of the essence-Qi, (2) and metabolism of body fluids.
The relationship between the lungs and the kidneys may be viewed mainly from two aspects: water metabolism and respiratory activities.
The Qi in the human body derives from the integration of three kinds of Qi, that is, the congenital Qi inherited from the parents, Qi from essence of foodstuff and fresh air inhaled from the external atmosphere, through the comprehensive action of the lungs, spleen, stomach, kidneys and other Zang-Fu organs.
Qi, as a vigorous essential substance, plays a promoting and activating role in the growth and development of the body, the physiological activities of various Zang-Fu orangs, channels and collaterals, the production and circulation of blood, the formation, distribution and excretion of body fluids, etc.
Nan Jing says:"Qi is responsible for warming the body." That is to say, it is the source of body heat.
The defense mechanism of the body against disease is very complicated and involves the coordinated action of Qi, blood, body fluids and Zang-Fu organs, channels, collaterals and other structures.
The Primordial Qi is also called"original Qi".
The pectoral Qi is composed of fresh air the lungs inhale from nature and the refined essence of food conveyed by the spleen.
Qi of the middle-Jiao refers to the functions of the spleen and stomach.
It is a vital essence circulating with the blood in channels.
The defensive Qi, characterized by swiftness and toughness, is also transformed from the essential substances of foods, but flows outside the vessels.
The movements or functional activities of Qi are called "functioning of Qi".
The fur getting thicker and thicker indicates unfavorable prognosis due to aggravation of a disease owing to exuberant pathogens. On the contrary, the fur getting thinner and thinner suggests a favorable prognosis due to predominance of vital Qi and gradual decline of the pathogen.
The nutritive Qi and body fluids are regarded as the principal material basis for blood formation.
To be full of vigour and to have perfect consciousness, keen perception and free movement, the human body depends on the blood for nourishment.
The body fluid performs two functions: moistening and nourishing.
As commander of blood, Qi performs three main functions: 1) the production of blood,2) the propelling of blood, and 3) the control of blood circulation.
By palpating the epigastrium for its hardness and tenderness upon pressure a doctor is in a position to differentiate the syndrome of fullness from the syndrome due to agglomeration of pathogens in chest.
Both body fluid and blood are derived from food essence, hence they are said to have"a common source".
The doctrine of meridian, or the theory of channels and collaterals, deals with the physiological functions, pathological changes of the system of the channels and collaterals and their relationship with the Zang-Fu organs.
By primary cause of a disease is meant the etiology and pathogenesis of its occurrence and development.
The meridian system consists of the channels, collaterals and their connective tissues.
In the region of the upper and lower limbs, the three Yin channels run along the medial aspect and the three Yang channels along the lateral aspect.
The three Yin channels and three Yang channels of both hand and foot are mutually linked up by their branches and major collaterals, forming six pairs of exterior-interior relations.
The"eight extra channels" is a collective term for Du, Ren, Chong, Dai, Yinqiao,-Yanqiao, Yinwei and Yangwei channels.
A pulse felt hasty and rapid, with irregular intermittence, is called running pulse.
Clinically, doctors attach much importance to stomach-Qi and usually regard preserving the stomach-Qi as an important principle of treatment.
The bile in the gallbladder is formed by the surplus of the liver-essence.
The collaterals distributed on the body surface are named "superficial collaterals".
The skin areas refer to the divisions on the skin of the body surface according to the distribution of the meridians.
A disease is commonly considered to be the outcome of imbalance between Yin and Yang, organic trauma and abnormality in physiological functions of the human body.
The occurrence of a disease refers to the condition in which under action of some pathogenic factors the human body loses the balance between Yin and Yang, its Zang-Fu organs are impaired and its normal physiological functions distrubed.
It refers to the cause or condition leading to the occurrence of a disease.
This is a general term for six exopathic pathogenic factors, namely, wind, cold summer-heat, dampness, dryness and fire.
The six climatic conditions in excess, pertaining to exopathic pathogenic agents, generally possess the following features: (1) Illness is commonly related to seasonal climates and natural environment one lives in.
Wind, prevailing in spririg, exists all the year round.
Cold, though prevalent in winter, is also very common in other seasons.
Summer-heat exists only in summer, resulting from fire.
Dampness, prevalent in the long summer, is also very common in other seasons.
Dryness, prevalent in autumn, can also be seen in other seasons.
Fire-heat, brought about by an excess of Yang, is interchangeably called fire or heat.
It is a highly infectious exogenic pathogen, which also bears the names of"Li Qi", "DuQi", or"YiQi", etc.
According to tradtional Chinese medicine, seven emothions refer to the seven emotional manifestations, namely, joy, anger, melancholy, meditation, grief, fear and terror.
Emotions are closely related to Qi and blood in internal organs.
Improper diet, such as underfeeding, overeating, insanitary food or food preference, is often the factor predisposing to disease.
Imbalance between work and rest, referring to overwork or undue leisure, may turn out to be a pathogenic factor.
When the essence in the kidney is replenished to a certain degree during youth, inside the body may be produced a kind of substance named "Tian Gui", which promotes the development and maturity of sex gland. Then, a male begins to produce and ejaculate semen, while a female starts to have a regular menstruation with ovulation, that is to say, he or she has possessed the reproductive power due to maturity of sex gland and is, therefore, said to reach puberty.
It is a pathological product resulting from disturbance in water metabolism.
When phlegm is formed, it flows together with Qi to all parts of the body, that is, internally to the Zang-Fu organs and externally to muscles and skin, thereby producing a variety of syndromes.
It is a pathological product resulting from abnormal circulation and stagnation of blood.
The factors contributing to blood stasis are numerous and varied, but it is due chiefly to stagnation of Qi, deficiency of Qi, blood-cold, blood-heat, etc.
When blood stasis is formed, blood not only fails to perform its nutritive function but instead hinders its systemic or local circulation, thereby producing various syndromes.
Vital Qi, also known as genuine Qi refers to the body's functional activities (including the functions of Zang-Fu organs, channels and collaterals, Qi and blood, etc.), and disease-resistant and rehabilitating capabilities, including its adaptation to natural environment, defense against exogenic pathogens, self-repair of injuries as well as readjustment to functional disturbance, etc.
A disease is the outcome of a struggle between pathogenic factors and vital Qi in which the former act upon the latter.
As is known, insufficiency of vital Qi is the intrinsic factor in the causation of disease.
The struggle between vital Qi and pathogens has not only a bearing on the causation of disease but also an influence upon its development and termination.
If, in the course of the struggle between vital Qi and pathogens, the latter are exuberant and the former relatively deficient, the latter will win a victory over the former, thus giving rise to imbalance between Yin and Yang, and Qi and blood in the Zang-Fu organs with a resultant disease.
The occurrence of disease is closely related to internal and external environment.
By wax or wane of vital Qi and pathogens are menat changes in prosperity or decline occurring in the mutual struggle between vital Qi and pathogens in the course of a disease.
Relative excessiveness of Yin or Yang may lead to an excess syndrome resulting from exuberant invading pathogens.
Cold syndrome due to Yang-deficiency is a generalization of the pathogenesis of insufficiency of the body's yang-Qi and production of endogenic cold of deficiency type.
Heat syndrome due to Yin-deficiency is a generalization of the pathogenesis of inadequacy of the body's Yin-fluid (inciuding essence of life, blood and body fluid) and production of endogenic heat of deficiency type.
It refers to the pathogenesis in which on condition that either Yin or Yang is impaired, its pathological changes will affect its opposite aspect, thus leading to deficiency of both Yin and Yang.
It is a morbid state in which sudden massive consumption or loss of Yin-fluid leads to severe general function failure.
Instead, the gallbladder stores refined juice, namely bile. In this sense, it is described as belonging to the extraordinary Fu-organs.
It is a morbid state due to consumption of Qi of the whole body, its dysfunction, hypofunction of the Zang-Fu organs and lowered resistance against diseases.
It refers to such pathological changes as stagnation of Qi, its reversed flow, collapse, obstruction, and exhaustion due to disturbance in its ascending-descending and incoming-outgoing functions.
Collapse of Qi, one of the pathogeneses of deficiency of Qi, is a morbid condition mainly characterized by invigorous ascending and descending of Qi.
It refers to a morbid state in which Qi is blocked up because of sudden obstruction of its external flow.
It refers to a morbid state characterized by sudden functional failure of Qi resulting from failure to be kept internally due to its external exhaustion.
It refers to a morbid state due to insufficiency of blood and hypofunction of its nourishment.
It refers to a morbid state caused by obstructed or sluggish flow of blood.
It is a morbid state due to heat in the blood system and speeding up of blood flow.
This is a morbid condition due to simultaneous occurrence of stagnation of Qi and blood stasis.
This is a morbid condition marked by various kinds of bleeding, in which the blood flow fails to be controlled due to the deficiency of Qi and extravasation results.
It is a morbid state showing exhaustion of Qi caused by massive bleeding with resultant deficiency and exhaustion of both Qi and blood.
It refers to a morbid state of abnormal movement or abnormal sensation of the limbs, tendons, muscles, etc, caused by deficiency of Qi and blood or derangement of Qi and blood.
Fluid metabolism is practically a process of constant production, distribution and excretion of body fluid.
It refers to a pathologic state marked by dryness, resulting from failure of body fluid (which is insufficient in quantity) to moisten and nourish the Zang-organs, pores, skin and hairs.
It refers to the pathologic state characterized by stagnation of Qi due to metabolic disturbance of body fluid and retention of water and phlegm.
It is a morbid state showing depletion of Qi due to loss of lodgement of body fluid, resulting from massive loss of body fluid. Its common causes are: consumption of body fluid by high fever, or profuse perspiration, or severe vomiting, or diarrhea.
It refers to the pathologic state showing extreme exhaustion of body fluid, leading to production of heat of deficiency-type inside the body and production of wind due to blood inadequacy.
It refers to a morbid condition characterized by stagnancy of blood due to loss of body fluid.
They refer to the five pathologic changes, namely, wind-transformation cold-transformation dampness-transformation dryness-transformation and fire-transformation resulting from disturbance in physiological functions of Qi, blood, body fluid and Zang-Fu organs.
Endogenous wind, also referred to as"wind stirring inside the body", is a morbid condition caused by hyperactivity and adverse flow of yang-Qi.
It is brought about by depletion of body fluid and insufficient blood, resulting from consumption of blood by protracted illness, or insufficiency of blood and essence in old people, or decreased production of blood due to chronic malnutrition, or disturbance in blood production due to blood stasis.
It is a morbid condition of internal cold or excess of Yin-cold due to deficiency of yang-Qi and its weakened warming function.
It indicates the morbid condition of retention of water and phlegm within the body, caused by disturbance of the spleen's transporting and distributing function.
Endogenous dryness, also known as syndrome of dryness, is a morbid condition characterized by insufficiency of body fluid, which fails to moisten the Zang-Fu organs, tissues and pores.
Endogenous heat, also known as pathogenic fire accumulated in the interior, is a pathologic state characterized by invasion of interior by pathogenic fire or hyperfunction due to excess of Yang, hyperactivity of Yang due to Yin deficiency, or stagnation of Qi and blood, or accumulation of pathogenic factors inside the body.
It indicates the intrinsic mechanism of disturbance in normal physiological functions of Zang-Fu organs in the process of a disease.
It is indicative of the heart-fire, usually resulting from pathogenic heat, stagnation of phlegm-fire, and disorders of five emotions.
Impairment, or deficiency, of the heart-blood, is often caused by loss of blood, or insufficiency of blood formation, or due to internal impairment by emotions, etc.
Deficiency, or insufficiency, of the lung-Yin is mainly due to impairment of the lungs by pathogenic dryness-heat, or stagnation of phlegm -fire inside the body, or disorders of five emotions in excess, or to consumption of the lung-Yin by protracted cough.
It is a morbid state further deteriorated from deficency of the spleen-Qi, or resulting from disturbance of the warming function of the spleen due to decline of the fire from"the gate of life". Deficiency of the spleen-Yang leads to endogenous cold of insufficiency type, manifested as cold-type pain of the abdomen, diarrhea with undigested food in stool, diarrhea before dawn, etc.
It is mainly caused by consumption of body fluid, resulting from dysfunction of the spleen due to deficiency of the spleen-Qi.
It is mostly caused by excessive loss of blood or weakened function of the spleen and stomach in blood production or consumption of blood by protracted illness.
It is mainly due to congenital deficiency, essence reduced with age, consumption of essence by protracted iHness, or lack of proper care after birth.
It is a morbid state mainly due to deficiency of the kidney-essence in children or decline of the kidney-essence in the aged, or chronic consumption of the kidney-Qi owing to early marriage or intemperance in sexual life, or protracted illness.
It is a morbid condition resulting chiefly from impairment of the stomach-Qi by a long-term improper diet, or congenitai weak constitution, or instability to recover from a protracted illness, etc.
It is a morbid state due to impairment of the stomach-Yang resulting from excessive intake of cold and raw food, or drugs of cold nature, or due to congenital insufficiency of Yang complicated by an attack of pathogenic cold on the middle-Jiao.
The diagnostic method refers to the four basic techniques for diagnosis, namely, inspection auscultation and olfaction, interrogation and palpation.
Inspection is a method of observing the patient's mental state, complexion, physical condition and behavior by the doctor's eye to gain clinical data concerning the disease.
Possession of vitality or vigour, is a manifestation of abundant Qi-blood of the Zang-Fu organs, commonly seen in a healthy person.
As the Qi-blood of the human body originates from the food and drink, the stomach is also called "the reservoir of Qi-blood from foodstuff ".
The red complexion is due to the upward replenishment of the face with the Qi and blood in their quick flow resulting from invasion of the pathogenic heat.
Observation of the ear, the specific orifice of the kidneys, refers mainly to inspection of its colour, shape and changes of its excretion.
Ruddy and lustrous lips indicate sufficiency of the stomach-Qi and the balance between Qi and blood.
The stomach is regarded as the reservoir of Qi-blood from foodstuff.
Being dominated by the lungs, the skin is most closely related to them.
The miliaria alba is a crystalline and millet-like vesicle, protruding from the skin, oozing watery fluid after being broken, and largely distributed over the skin of the neck, chest and nape.
The tongue, as the sprout of the heart, is related directly or indirectly to a lot of Zang-Fu organs through the meridians.
A tongue with red colour deeper than normal is named the red tongue, indicating heat syndrome.
Since Nan Jing advanced a view that "Tri-Jiao exists merely nominally, it is not the entity of an organ". This Fu-organ aroused much controversy in later ages. However, it is generally accepted that the main functions of Tri-Jiao are to pass various kinds of Qi and to circulate body fluids.
A tongue smaller than normal in size is called emaciated tongue, a manifestation of failure of the collateral vessels in the tongue body to be replenished and nourished by the Qi and blood and Yin fluid.
The tongue with tooth prints at its borders is known as the indented, or teeth-printed tongue as a result of the pressure of dental coronae upon the puffy tongue.
The rigid tongue body with inability to move freely is called the stiff tongue.
The whitish and thin fur is usually seen in an exterior syndrome or a cold syndrome.
The yellow fur, resulting from steaming of the pathogenic heat, chiefly indicates heat syndrome.
The grey fur indicates an interior syndrome, which may be cold or heat in nature.
The black fur usually appears in the critical stage of an epidemic febrile disease, indicating the interior syndrome, either cold or heat in nature.
The thin fur refers to a thin layer of coating through which the tongue body can be indistinctly seen.
The amount of body fluid may be estimated by observing the moisture of the fur.
The tongue fur, exfoliating completely or partiatly, is known as exfoliative.
Here the functions of the spleen and stomach in decomposing, transporting and transforming foodstuff are compared to a fermentative process.
The sputum is a pathological product formed in the course of water metabolism of the body, closely related to the lungs and spleen.
The phlegm and food coming out of the mouth owing to adverse rising of the stomach-Qi are named vomitus.
Abnormal colour and nature of stool may reflect pathologic changes in the spleen, stomach and intestines and cold-syndrome or heat-syndrome, deficiency-syndrome or excess-syndrome of a disease as well.
Normal urine is a light yellowish fluid.
The superficial venules of the infant's fingers refer to collateral vessels emerging on the palmar aspect of the index fingers of a child, which are the branches of the Lung Channel of Hand-Taiyin, so they may reflect the changes of Qi and blood of Zang-Fu organs.
The doctrine of visceral phase, attributing the physiological functidns and pathological changes of the brain to the heart and respectively to the five Zang-organs, holds that " Like a king, the heart governs all the vital functions of the whole body, including mental activities", and "as the dominator of the five Zang-organs and six Fu-organs, it houses the mind".
A passage from chapter Da Huo of Lingshu says: "The vital essence of the five Zang-organs and six Fu-organs all flows up into the eyes and provides the material basis for visual function", and the ocular connectors "communicate with the brain".
The stomach dominates the reception of food, while the spleen governs its transportation and transformation. The relationship between them may be summarized as follows: "The spleen transports the nutrients for the stomach", both organs jointly accomplishing the digestion of food and absorption and distribution of food essence which nourishes the entire body. Therefore, the spleen and the stomach together "provide a material basis for the acquired constitution".
Auscultation and olfaction are the diagnostic method of detecting the clinical status of a patient by listening (to his voice, breathing, coughing) and smelling (odor of his secretion and excretion).
Voice is produced by coordinative activities of the larynx, epiglottis, tongue, lips, teeth and nose, etc., and by functional activities of vital Qi in particular.
A loud and sonorous speech sound often indicates excess syndrome, or heat syndrome, while a low and faint speech sound or disinclination to talk usually denotes deficiency syndrome or cold syndrome, as a result of the serenity of Yin and the mobility of Yang.
Since the lungs control respiration and the kidneys regulate inspiration, abnormal breathing is mainly related to the lungs and kidneys.
Foul breath is due to indigestion or dirty mouth, belcning with sour and fetid oder or disgust for the odour of food denotes food stagnancy.
Only in so doing can their functional activities be maintained in a harmonious state. This is what is known as "coordination between the heart and the kidneys", or "mutual assistance of fire and water".
This indicates that both symptoms occur at the same time as a result of accumulation of exogenous pathogens on the superficies with a consequent combat between them and defensive Qi.
This is a symptom suggesting that the patient with fever has an aversion to heat but not to cold, which pertains to interior heat syndrome; resulting from excess of Yang or hyperactivity of Yang due to deficiency of Yin.
Alternate spells of chills and fever are manifestations of half exterior and half interior syndrome seen in Shaoyang syndrome or malaria.
Frequent sweating, which intensifies on exertion, is known as spontaneous perspiration, mostly caused by deficiency of both Qi and Yang bringing about lowering superficial resistance and letting out of body fluid due to loose of the striae.
As the saying goes: "The spleen serves as the source of sputum and the lungs as its container".
For example, dysfunction of the liver in governing normal flow of Qi may affect the spleen, resulting in a morbid condition called "incoordination between the liver and the spleen".
Since the liver stores blood and the kidneys store essence, and the blood and essence promote each other and transform themselves into each other, the liver and the kidneys form a close relationship with each other because of the fact that they come from the same source.
The essence stored in the kidneys relies also on the replenishment of Qi-blood transformed from foodstuff.
Since the chest is the place where the heart and the lungs are located, pain in the chest is mostly related to these two organs.
The stomach functions to receive food and is characterized by descending.
The Chong channel is also known as "The reservoir of blood".since it is closely related to menstruation in female.
Arthralgia is a Bi-syndrome often resulting from attack of the meridians by pathogenic wind, cold and dampness or heat-transformation from persistent stagnation of the three pathogens.
Pain with distension is indicative of stagnation of Qi.
Pricking pain like stabbing with a thorn is a clinical characteristic of blood stasis, often caused by trauma or stagnation of Qi leading to accumulation of blood in localized regions.
Radiuating pain or referred pain is usually caused by blockage of meridians with a resultant deficiency of Qi and blood.
The condition of sleeping is closely linked with circulation of, defensive Qi and ups and downs of Yin and Yang.
Drowsiness, referring to frequent uncontrollable sleepiness, accompanied by dizziness and heavy head, is caused by excess of Yin due to Yang-deficiency or impairment of the spleen-Yang by dampness, often seen in epidemic febrile disease characterized by attack of the pericardium by heat.
Since the spleen and stomach perform the function of receiving and digesting food, the appetite and taste are related to the functional condition of the spleen and stomach.
Thirst and drinking can reflect the vicissitudes and distribution of body fluid.
However, when the six natural factors are excessive or deficient due to abnormal changes in weather; or when these factors change so rapidly (such as sudden attack of cold or hot weather) as to exceed the body's resistance; or when the body's resistance declines so rapidly owing to deficiency of the vital Qi as to be unable to adapt itself to the changes in weather, these natural factors turn out to be pathogenic agents, known as "six climatic conditions in excess as pathogenic factors".
Under normal conditions little discharge from the vagina is odourless and milky white liquid.
There may often appear rheumatic arthritis manifested by the symptoms of severe pain in the joints and aversion to cold, known as "arthralgia due to attack of cold".
Palpation is one of the four methods of physical examination, including pulse-taking and palpation of the body.
It is also a diagnostic method whereby a, doctor can examine pulse condition, detect condition of illness and gather clinical data through palpating the pulsation of the radial arteries with his or her finger-tips.
Therefore, the dysfunction of Qi and blood in the five Zang-organs will bring about abnormality of emotional activities accordingly.
Firm pulse is one forceful, large, taut and long, felt only by pressing hard, and usually seen in obstinate diseases with accumulation of Yin cold, such as abdominal mass, and hernia, etc.
Slow pulse is one with less than four beats to a normal cycle of respiration (less than sixty beats per minute), indicating cold syndrome.
Rapid pulse is one with 5-6 beats to a normal cycle of respiration (from 91-120 beats per minute), generally indicating heat syndrome.
A pulse, felt floating, thready and forceless by light touch, but faint on heavy press, is called soft pulse, indicating both deficiency sydnrome and dampness syndrome.
A tense pulse is one felt tense and forceful, like a stretched twisted cord, usually indicating cold syndrome.
A pulse felt hasty and rapid (more than 90 beats per minute), with irregular intermittence, is called running pulse.
This refers to a pulse with long extent and prolonged stroke.
